0. Introduction and Business Understanding¶

Introduction¶

In this lab, we will use different machine learning algorithms for our two main tasks documented below.

  1. Run predictive model to predict wage from players abilities (regression models). We will select some features to run regression models. Also, we will try running LDA and regression model. To measure the effectiveness, we will use RMSE, MAE and R squared.

  2. Run classification model to classify players (classification models) position from the players ability. To validate our models, we will use accuracy, precision, F1 score and ROC.

We carry over the Business Understanding and Data Preparation from Lab 1. More information related to Visualization and Data Preprocessing can be found in Lab 1.

Business Understanding¶

Kaggle dataset (https://www.kaggle.com/stefanoleone992/fifa-20-complete-player-dataset) players_20.csv is used in this lab. The dataset provides detailed information of all the soccer players statistics in various clubs of major soccer leagues in the world. The data is originally from the FIFA soccer game created by EA sports. This game estimates the abilities of the actual players and built the game according to the data. And the Kaggle dataset is scraped from www.sofifa.com, where the gaming data is collected. The data we used is last updated on Sept 19th 2019.

The dataset is important because the abilities of players is estimated from the actual players. FIFA is a very popular game and EA Sports is one of the largest sport video game developer. The player abilities estimate is quite accurate. Therefore, useful knowledge can be mined from the data for analyzing variety problems in the soccer industry. For example, wage analysis, player analysis, training strategy, budget analysis, sport gambling strategy plan can be performed using this dataset. Soccer has been a big industry which the market size is estimated to worth $488 billion in 2018 according to the Business Wire.

1. Data Preparation Part I¶

In this subsection, we deal with missing values, converting data types to appropriate ones. We will also divide the soccers players into 4 groups meaningfully as Defending (DEF), Forward (FWD), Midfield (MID) and Goal Keeper (GK) to learn from existing dataset to predict new players potential positions based on their skillset. We will come with our final cleaned dataset for our regression and classification task's.

Note: We will reserve the data scaling to Part 2 subsection while preparing the test/train dataset.

Due to the large number of features we have created a csv file that will serve as a metadata file as follows
1) File location: ../data/fifa20/data_desc.csv
2) The Name column as the exact name that is in our original dataset file and we will use this to load the file.
3) Description: The team has filled up the description of each feature describing it.
4) Variable_cat: We use this to categorise related features for example 'Position' indicates all the features related to various position attirbutes.
Using a metadata makes it easy in case we want to ignore certain attributes that are not relavant for our analysis by marking it as Ignore.

This image helps us understand various positions that a soccer players is assigned during a game. The feature player_positions represents multiple positions that a player can play in with a comma seperate value, the very first item in that list has a preferred field position of the player. The team_position is the current positon that the player is being used in the team. For our analysis we will use the players preferred positon.

The statistics of each individual player ability in respective positons are in seperate features on a scale of 1 to 100 as described in the table output aboive.

A goal keeper does not occupy any of the positions that a regular player occupies under normal circumstances which means he will not have any specific statistics for those features. A goal keeper on the other hand has a different set of features to capture his statistics, these are displayed in the table above in the Variable_cat field as 'GK'.

Refactor position features [Object to discrete]¶

The position features inculdes year over improvement / decrement. For example a player in st (Striker) position with a value of 89+2 is basically 89 with an increase (- would indicate decrease) of 2 from last year. Since we will not be doing any year over analysis, we will remove the suffix for these columns = ['ls','st','rs','lw','lf','cf','rf', 'rw','lam','cam','ram', 'lm','lcm','cm','rcm','rm','lwb','ldm', 'cdm','rdm', 'rwb','lb','lcb', 'cb','rcb','rb']

Dealing with missing values¶

The player positional features mentioned above and the skills features ['pace','shooting', 'passing','dribbling', 'defending','physic'] have a total of 2036 missing values. We see that all of them are categorized to play in the GK position (player_positions="GK", Goal Keeper). We will set these values to zero.

Goal Keeper specific attributes¶

The following features ['gk_diving','gk_handling','gk_kicking','gk_reflexes', 'gk_speed','gk_positioning'] are specific to goalkeepers. We see a total of 16242 mising values, which corrosponds to the non goalkeeper or regular positional players. We will set these values to zero. Also there are duplicate columns representing these same attributes which we will ignore ['goalkeeping_diving', 'goalkeeping_handling', 'goalkeeping_kicking', 'goalkeeping_positioning', 'goalkeeping_reflexes']

Reducing dataset and scaling them¶

Classification Task¶

In Lab 1 analysis, we identified our regressor variables that we plan to use for our two tasks. There are a total of 31 features which include the players mental, attacking, skills, movements, defending, power, height and weight attributes. We will reduce the dataset as follows.

  1. Classifying players' position: In addition to the above mentioned 31 features we will inclue the feature preferred_position_cat that identifies the players on the four positional categories.

3. Modeling and Evaluation 1¶

Task 1. Classification¶

We classify players positions by using the players abilities variables by four main positions Defending (DEF), Forward (FWD), Midfield (MID) and Goal Keeper (GK). Since we have imbalanced classes, f1 score is a better metric to evaluate our models. We will use the f1 score to evaluate the machine learning models in this lab. This score can be interpreted as a weighted average of the precision and recall where its best value is at 1 and its worst score is at 0. The relative contribution of precision and recall to the f1 score are equal. Here is the formula to show how the f1 score is calculated

f1 = 2 * (precision * recall) / (precision + recall).
In the above formula, precision means the percentage of your results which are relevant. On the other hand, recall refers to the percentage of total relevant results correctly classified by your algorithm. The metric f1 score is simply the harmonic mean of precision and recall.

In the multi-class and multi-label case, for example, in our study, with 4 classes DEF, FWD, MID and GK, the overall f1 score is the average of the f1 score of each class with weighting depending on the average parameter.

Task 2. Regression¶

In this task, we use Root mean square error (RMSE) and Mean absolute error (MAE) as the two metrics to measure accuracy of the regression models. MAE measures the average magnitude of the errors in a set of predictions without considering their direction. It is the average over the test sample of the absolute differences between prediction and actual observation where all individual differences have equal weight. $$ MAE = \frac{1}{n}\sum^n_{j=1} |y_j - \hat{y}_j|. $$ In the other hand, RMSE is a quadratic scoring rule that also measures the average magnitude of the error. It’s the square root of the average of squared differences between prediction and actual observation. $$ RMSE = \sqrt{\frac{1}{n}\sum^n_{j=1} (y_j - \hat{y}_j)^2}. $$ The MAE and the RMSE can be used together to predict wage from players abilities. The RMSE will always be larger or equal to the MAE; the greater difference between them, the greater the variance in the individual errors in the sample. If the RMSE=MAE, then all the errors are of the same magnitude. Both the MAE and RMSE can range from $0$ to $\infty$. They are negatively-oriented scores: Lower values are better.

We also show MAPE (Mean Absolute Percent Error) and $R^2$ in the report. However, we focus the evaluations on RMSE and MAE. $R^2$ suffers considerable abuse. It is rarely an appropriate statistic to use for model checking, model comparison or inference.

# Adapted from:
# https://www.featureranking.com/tutorials/machine-learning-tutorials/information-gain-computation/
def gini_index(y):
    probs = pd.value_counts(y,normalize=True)
    return 1 - np.sum(np.square(probs))

def plot_class_dist(y):
    class_ct = len(np.unique(y['preferred_position_cat']))
    vc = pd.value_counts(y['preferred_position_cat'])
    print('Total Records', len(y['preferred_position_cat']))
    print('Total Classes:', class_ct)
    print('Class Gini Index', gini_index(y['preferred_position_cat']))
    print('Smallest Class Id:',vc.idxmin(),'Records:',vc.min())
    print('Largest Class Id:',vc.idxmax(),'Records:',vc.max())
    print('Accuracy when Guessing:', np.round( (1 / len(np.unique(y['preferred_position_cat']))) * 100, 2), '%')
    
    position_counts = pd.DataFrame(y['preferred_position_cat'].value_counts())
    position_counts['Percentage'] = position_counts['preferred_position_cat']/position_counts.sum()[0]
    print(position_counts)
    plt.figure(figsize=(4,4))

    plt.pie(position_counts['Percentage'],labels = ['DEF', 'FWD', 'MID', 'GK'],  autopct='%1.1f%%');

evaluate_clf_model_performance methods uses a grid searchCV scikitlearn api to evaluate a set of models that are passed to it. The best performing model is identified with the graphs show comparative statistics. The evaluation is done as follows:
 model_name: string representing the model name can be anything
 params: List of model tuning paramters
 clf: the estimator classification to evaluate
 X_train, y_train: The scaled train dataset, the grid search will use this data set and run internal CV to evaluate the model passed
 X_test, y_test: this test data set for best model estimated.
 nCV: Number of cross validation to run

Returns :
 modal_stats: a summary of best model

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
def evaluate_clf_model_performance(model_name, params, clf, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, nCV = 10, n_jobs =4):
    # We prepare the grid search object
    grid = gridcv(clf, params, cv=nCV,scoring='accuracy',n_jobs =-1, refit=True )
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    model_stat =  pd.DataFrame()
    model_stat['model_name'] =[str(model_name)]

    res = grid.cv_results_
    #print(res)
    # Lets store the scores for t-test validation of models
    cvscore = cross_val_score(grid.best_estimator_, X_train, y_train, scoring='f1_weighted', cv=nCV,n_jobs= n_jobs)

    model_stat['scores'] = [cvscore]
    #grid.cv_results_.keys()
    res.keys()
    #res['params']
    grid_scr = pd.DataFrame()
    grid_scr['params'] = res['params']
    grid_scr['mean_test_score'] = res['mean_test_score']
    grid_scr = pd.DataFrame(grid_scr)
    #print(grid_scr)

    grid_scr.plot.bar(color='grey',figsize=(10,6))
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
    plt.xlabel('Params')
    plt.grid(color='blue', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5)
    plt.ylim(0.5,.95)

    print("Best parameters set found on development set:")
    print()
    print(grid.best_params_)
    #model_stat['score'] = [grid.best_score_]
    print()
    print("Grid scores on development set:")
    print()
    means = res['mean_test_score']

    stds = res['std_test_score']
    for mean, std, params in zip(means, stds, res['params']):
        print("%0.5f (+/-%0.03f) for %r"
              % (mean, std * 2, params))
    print()

    print("Detailed classification report:")
    print()
    print("The model is trained on the full development set.")
    print("The scores are computed on the full evaluation set.")
    print()
    #build CM using test/Train
    y_true, y_pred = y_test, grid.predict(X_test)
    #y_pred
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=['DEF', 'FWD', 'GK','MID']))
    s = classification_report(y_true, y_pred, target_names=['DEF', 'FWD', 'GK','MID'])
    model_stat['CM'] = s
    plot_confusion_matrix(grid, X_test,y_test,cmap=plt.cm.Blues,values_format='d')
    model_stat['time_refit'] = [grid.refit_time_]
    model_stat['model_param'] = [str(grid.best_params_)]
    model_stat['weighted_f1_score']=round(f1_score(y_true, y_pred, average='weighted'),2)
    #model_stat['accuracy']=accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    plt.grid(b=None);
    print()
    return model_stat

Custom Scorers for Evaluating Regression Models¶

All regression models created in this notebook are validated using the following metrics:

  • Mean Absolute Error (MAE)
  • Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/17197492/root-mean-square-error-in-python
  • Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42250958/how-to-optimize-mape-code-in-python
  • R^2 (R2) - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/59315992/cross-validation-in-r-vs-scikit-learn-for-linear-regression-r2

Helper method

In [36]:
#Use mean absolute error (MAE) to score the regression models created 
#(the scale of MAE is identical to the response variable)
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, make_scorer, mean_squared_error, r2_score

#Function for Root mean squared error
#https://stackoverflow.com/questions/17197492/root-mean-square-error-in-python
def rmse(y_actual, y_predicted):
    return np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_actual, y_predicted))

#Function for Mean Absolute Percentage Error (MAPE) - Untested
#Adapted from - https://stackoverflow.com/questions/42250958/how-to-optimize-mape-code-in-python
def mape(y_actual, y_predicted): 
    mask = y_actual != 0
    return (np.fabs(y_actual - y_predicted)/y_actual)[mask].mean() * 100

#Create scorers for rmse and mape functions
mae_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=mean_absolute_error, greater_is_better=False)
rmse_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=rmse, greater_is_better=False)
mape_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=mape, greater_is_better=False)
r2_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=r2_score, greater_is_better=True)

#Make scorer array to pass into cross_validate() function for producing mutiple scores for each cv fold.
errorScoring = {'MAE':  mae_scorer, 
                'RMSE': rmse_scorer,
                'MAPE': mape_scorer,
                'R2': r2_scorer,
                }

from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate
import seaborn as sns
# colors = ["windows blue", "amber", "greyish", "faded green", "dusty purple"]
# pal = sns.xkcd_palette(colors)
import pprint

def EvaluateRegressionEstimator(regEstimator, X, y, cv):
    
    scores = cross_validate(regEstimator, X, y, scoring=errorScoring, cv=cv, return_train_score=True)
    #print('scores = \n')
    #pp = pprint.PrettyPrinter(indent=1)
    #pp.pprint(scores)

    #cross val score sign-flips the outputs of MAE
    # https://github.com/scikit-learn/scikit-learn/issues/2439
    scores['test_MAE'] = scores['test_MAE'] * -1
    scores['test_MAPE'] = scores['test_MAPE'] * -1
    scores['test_RMSE'] = scores['test_RMSE'] * -1  

    #print mean MAE for all folds 
    maeAvg = scores['test_MAE'].mean()
    print_str = "The average MAE for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {maeAvg:.5}"
    print(print_str.format(maeAvg=maeAvg))

    #print mean test_MAPE for all folds
    scores['test_MAPE'] = scores['test_MAPE']
    mape_avg = scores['test_MAPE'].mean()
    print_str = "The average MAE percentage (MAPE) for all cv folds is: \t {mape_avg:.5}"
    print(print_str.format(mape_avg=mape_avg))

    #print mean MAE for all folds 
    RMSEavg = scores['test_RMSE'].mean()
    print_str = "The average RMSE for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {RMSEavg:.5}"
    print(print_str.format(RMSEavg=RMSEavg))
    
    #print mean R2 for all folds 
    R2avg = scores['test_R2'].mean()
    print_str = "The average R2 for all cv folds is: \t\t\t {R2avg:.5}"
    print(print_str.format(R2avg=R2avg))    
    print('*********************************************************')

    print('Cross Validation Fold Mean Error Scores')
    scoresResults = pd.DataFrame()
    scoresResults['MAE'] = scores['test_MAE']
    scoresResults['MAPE'] = scores['test_MAPE']
    scoresResults['RMSE'] = scores['test_RMSE']
    scoresResults['R2'] = scores['test_R2']
    print(scoresResults)
    return scoresResults

def plot_kde_y_yhat(y, y_):
    plot_df = pd.DataFrame()
    plot_df['y'] = y
    plot_df['yhat'] = y_
    
    # Change negative yhat to 0 as wage can't be negative value
    plot_df[plot_df['yhat']<0] = 0
    ax1 = sns.distplot(plot_df['y'], kde=True, color='#4472C4', hist=False, label='Actual wages')
    sns.distplot(plot_df['yhat'], kde=True, color='#FF9900', hist=False, label='Predicted wages', ax=ax1)
    ax1.set(xlim=(-10000,150000))
    ax1.set_title("Actual wages vs. Predicted wages")
    plt.xlabel('Wages (€)')
    plt.ylabel('Gaussian Kernel Density Estimate')

%matplotlib inline

def evaluate_reg_model_performance(model_name,params,clf,score,X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test,nCV=10,n_jobs=-1):
    # We prepare the grid search object
    # and custom scorer
    mape_scorer = make_scorer(score_func=mape, greater_is_better=False)
    scoring = {'RMSE': 'neg_root_mean_squared_error',
               'MAE': 'neg_mean_absolute_error',
               'MAPE': mape_scorer,
               'R2': 'r2'}
    
    grid = gridcv(clf, params, cv=nCV, scoring=scoring, n_jobs=n_jobs, refit=score, return_train_score=True)
    grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
    model_stat = pd.DataFrame()
    model_stat['model_name'] = [str(model_name)]
    print("Best parameters set found:")
    print(grid.best_params_)
    res = grid.cv_results_
    #pp = pprint.PrettyPrinter(indent=1)
    #pp.pprint(res)
    
    grid_scr = pd.DataFrame()
    grid_scr['params'] = res['params']
    grid_scr['RMSE'] = -res['mean_test_RMSE']    
    grid_scr['MAPE'] = -res['mean_test_MAPE']
    grid_scr['MAE'] = -res['mean_test_MAE']
    grid_scr['R2'] = res['mean_test_R2']
    grid_scr = pd.DataFrame(grid_scr)
    print('\nMean score summary of each gridsearch estimator executed')
    #display(Markdown(grid_scr.to_markdown()))    
    
    x = np.arange(len(grid_scr['params'])).astype(int)
    
    plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 6))

    plt.subplot(221)
    plt.bar(x, grid_scr['RMSE'])
    plt.ylabel('RMSE')
    #plt.xlabel('Parameter')
    plt.title('RMSE mean scores (nCV=%i)'%nCV)
    plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.3)
    
    plt.subplot(222)
    plt.bar(x, grid_scr['MAPE'])
    plt.ylabel('MAPE')
    #plt.xlabel('Parameter')
    plt.title('MAPE mean scores (nCV=%i)'%nCV)
    plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.3)

    plt.subplot(223)
    plt.bar(x, grid_scr['MAE'])
    plt.ylabel('MAE')
    plt.xlabel('Parameter')
    plt.title('MAE mean scores (nCV=%i)'%nCV)
    plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.3)
    
    plt.subplot(224)
    plt.bar(x, grid_scr['R2'])
    plt.ylabel('R2')
    plt.xlabel('Parameter')
    plt.title('R2 mean scores (nCV=%i)'%nCV)
    plt.grid(color='grey', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.3)
    
    plt.subplots_adjust(left=0.125, right=0.8, wspace=0.3, hspace=0.4)
    plt.show()    
    
    print(nCV, 'fold cross validation average scores of the best Estimator found by GridSearchCV\n')
    e = EvaluateRegressionEstimator(grid.best_estimator_, X_train, y_train, nCV)
    model_stat['model_name']
    model_stat['RMSE'] = grid_scr['RMSE']
    model_stat['MAPE'] = grid_scr['MAPE']
    model_stat['MAE'] = grid_scr['MAE']
    model_stat['R2'] = grid_scr['R2']
    #display(Markdown(e.to_markdown()))
    #prediction
    
    if model_name in ['Linear Reg', 'Lasso Reg', 'Ridge Reg', 'Linear Reg_LDA', 'Lasso Reg_LDA', 'Ridge Reg_LDA']:
        plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 4))
        plt.subplot(121)
        grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
        yhat = grid.predict(X_test)
        plot_kde_y_yhat(y_test, yhat)

        plt.subplot(122)
        visualizer = ResidualsPlot(clf)
        visualizer.fit(X_train, y_train)
        visualizer.score(X_test, y_test)
        visualizer.show()
        plt.show()

        plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(13,4))    
        plt.subplot(121)
        visualizer = PredictionError(clf)
        visualizer.fit(X_train, y_train)
        visualizer.score(X_test, y_test)
        visualizer.finalize()

        plt.subplot(122)
        visualizer = CooksDistance()
        visualizer.fit(X_test, y_test)
        visualizer.finalize()
        plt.show()
    else:
        grid.fit(X_train, y_train)
        yhat = grid.predict(X_test)
        plot_kde_y_yhat(y_test, yhat)
    
    yhat_df = pd.DataFrame(yhat)
    yhat_df = yhat_df.rename({0: model_name}, axis='columns')    
    
    return (model_stat, yhat_df)

9. Support Vector Machines (SMOTE sampling)¶

SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling) works by selecting examples that are close in the feature space, drawing a line between the examples in the feature space and drawing a new sample at a point along that line. Specifically, a random example from the minority class is first chosen. Then k of the nearest neighbors for that example are found (typically k=5). A randomly selected neighbor is chosen and a synthetic example is created at a randomly selected point between the two examples in feature space.
şş https://machinelearningmastery.com/smote-oversampling-for-imbalanced-classification/

We use Synthetic Minority Over-sampling to over sample all classes, except the majority.
Original data: DEF:7362, FWD:4588, MID:4292, GK:2036
The dataset is increased from 18,278 records to 29,448 with each class containing 7,362 records.

Since SMOTE sampling performed real good in LR we will try this sampling stratergy using SVC. We reduced parameters and cv for model testing in the final paper as the SMOTE SVC takes a lot of procesing time.

# Plot the new class distributions for y using the same funnction as above. 
def plot_class_dist_1(players_y):
    fig, axarr = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(18, 6))
    class_ct = len(np.unique(players_y))
    vc = pd.value_counts(players_y)
    print('Total Records', len(players_y))
    print('Total Classes:', class_ct)
    print('Class Gini Index', gini_index(players_y))
    print('Smallest Class Id:',vc.idxmin(),'Records:',vc.min())
    print('Largest Class Id:',vc.idxmax(),'Records:',vc.max())
    print('Accuracy when Guessing:', np.round( (1 / len(np.unique(players_y))) * 100, 2), '%')

    sns.distplot(players_y, ax=axarr[0], bins=class_ct).set_title('Minilab Class Distribution');
    sns.distplot(players_y, ax=axarr[1], kde=False, bins=class_ct).set_title('Minilab Class Counts');

from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE

# Oversample using SMOTE
# Make all classes the same size as the majority class.
# WARNING - This can exponentially increase the size of the input dataset.
sm = SMOTE(sampling_strategy='not majority')
X_clf_sm, y_clf_sm = sm.fit_sample(X_players_clf_scaled, players_clf_y)

import altair as alt
def plot_alt_test(df, attr,best_model):
    alt1 = alt.Chart(df).mark_bar().encode(
        y = alt.Y('model_name',
                  title = 'Model Name',
                  sort = alt.EncodingSortField(field=attr, order='ascending')
                 ),
        x = alt.X(attr,
                  title = attr+' scores of each model'             
                 ),
        color = alt.condition(
            alt.datum.model_name == best_model,
            alt.value('orange'),
            alt.value('steelblue'))
        ).properties(
            title='Best Model (Orange) With '+attr+' Scores',
            width = 300,
            height = 300
        )
    return alt1

    visualizer.fit(X_train, y_train)        # Fit the training data to the visualizer
    visualizer.score(X_test, y_test)        # Evaluate the model on the test data

Method to calculate 955 CI and t-stats

In [75]:
from scipy import stats
from math import sqrt
from scipy.stats import t
def compare_models(model_name1, model_name2, acc1, acc2):
    
    # Run independent t-test
    ind_t_test = stats.ttest_ind(acc1,acc2)
    print(ind_t_test)
    # Calculate the mean difference and 95% confidence interval
    N1 = 3
    N2 = 3
    df = (N1 + N2 - 2)
    std1 = acc1.std()
    std2 = acc2.std()
    std_N1N2 = sqrt( ((N1 - 1)*(std1)**2 + (N2 - 1)*(std2)**2) / df) 
    diff_mean = acc1.mean() - acc2.mean()
    MoE = t.ppf(0.975, df) * std_N1N2 * sqrt(1/N1 + 1/N2)


    print('t-test for {}-{}: \n\tt-statistic = {:4.3f}\n\tp-value = {:4.3f}'.format(model_name1, model_name2,ind_t_test[0],ind_t_test[1]))
    print ('\nThe difference between groups is {:3.5f} [{:3.5f} to {:3.5f}] (mean [95% CI])'.format(diff_mean, diff_mean - MoE, diff_mean + MoE))

8. Modeling and Evaluation 6¶

A. Position Classification Model¶

The feature importances can be calculated using the Mean decrease in the gini index. Essentially, every time a feature is tested for splitting, the decrease in the gini (or entropy) is saved. The importance of the feature can then be approximated by taking the mean decrease in the gini for all the nodes where the feature is tested (usually the feature is tested at every node): $$ Imp_{A} = \frac{1}{|T|}\sum_{t \in T} gini_A(p_t) - gini_A(t) $$ where $|T|$ is the total number of nodes in the tree, $T$ is the set of all nodes, $gini_A(t)$ is the gini for the $A^{th}$ attribute at node $t$, and $gini_A(p_t)$ is the gini for the $A^{th}$ attribute at the parent node for $t$.

In this way, we have the mean decrease in the gini for attribute $A$. We can make a vector of these importance for all attributes in the dataset: $[Imp_1, Imp_2, ... Imp_{A_{tot}}]$.

scikit-learn computes this value for you and it is stored inside the tree object as dt_clf.feature_importances_. For the current dataset, there are feature vectors of size 31 skills. Therefore, we can look at the importances as a bar graph with 31 corresponding instances.

Feature Importances from Decision Tree¶

The following attribute are the most important in our decision tree model using the original dataset:
defending_sliding_tackle, mentality_positioning, attacking_finishing, defending_marking, mentality_vision, attacking_heading_accuracy, attacking_crossing, skill_long_passing

These variables are more important because they are position specific variables. For example, a defending (DEF) player has a higher marking and tackling in general because the position focus on defending attacking players. A forward (FWD) player in general has a much higher attacking finishing skill because he needs to focus on making goals.

Unlike the logistic regression, many of the attributes importance are close to zero, which means they are less important to the decision tree model. One of the results is decision tree use gini index or entropy to branch. The feature importance is calculated as the decrease in node impurity weighted by the probability of reaching that node. Therefore, the importance is higher coorelated to how the tree is branched.

B. Salary Estimate Regression Model¶

Feature Importance from Random Forest Model¶

https://www.scikit-yb.org/en/latest/api/model_selection/importances.html The feature engineering process involves selecting the minimum required features to produce a valid model because the more features a model contains, the more complex it is (and the more sparse the data), therefore the more sensitive the model is to errors due to variance. A common approach to eliminating features is to describe their relative importance to a model, then eliminate weak features or combinations of features and re-evalute to see if the model fairs better during cross-validation.
Many model forms describe the underlying impact of features relative to each other. In scikit-learn, Decision Tree models and ensembles of trees such as Random Forest, Gradient Boosting, and Ada Boost provide a featureimportances attribute when fitted. The Yellowbrick FeatureImportances visualizer utilizes this attribute to rank and plot relative importances.

The overall, movement reactions, attacking short passing, age, power shot power are the higher 5 important features in our Random Forest Regression model. The overall feature is a combined value of all the skills. It is much more important than all other features.

The detail positions are the least important features to the model. Surprisingly, the international reputation is not very important to the model. The rest of the features are not with very close importance value.

9. Deployment¶

Soccer clubs will be interested in our analyses. The Random Forest or Extra Tree model provide estimate of soccer players salary predictions. Clubs can offer salary when acquiring players base on the predictions. Also, the predictions can be a good reference when negotiating salary. The position classification task will provide good insight when coach prepare a team training strategy. Coach can decide the position of a player should play base on the prediction. And when switching positions of a player, coach can prepare a better strategy of what skills should the player focus on.

When a club is considering to trade players, we can deploy our models. For trading players, we can select players who the estimate salary are in the range of the budget. When there is a player the club wants to acquire, depending on how much desire the club wants to player, club can take the estimate salary as a reference. If the club thinks the player will fit well, it may offer salary that is higher than the estimate salary from our model. Also, when acquiring younger and newer players, the estimate salary can be a good reference because our model is driven by players' skills. We should collect the players' contract information so we can find out which players can be traded. Also, we can scrub players related news data so we can better understand players desires or preference.

The model need to be updated before trading windows or when club has a plan to trade a player. The running time for the deployment is not significant because the size of the data is small.
